snippet.textDisplay: The over Diagnosing of ADHD has become a problem. we as a society that is obsessed with labeling, classifying, and stratification, need to understand that labeling does not help in MOST cases when it comes to human beings. The stigma behind being labeled can create a feeling of self fulfilling prophecy. Joyner’s message is clear in that diagnosing is not proper solution for people who are perceived as not being able to focus or stay still. What I can affirm is that ADHD is a real diagnosis. But it should be diagnosed after childhood which is when children are naturally hyper and cannot hold attention do to their taking in of all the information life has to offer. I didn’t mean to write a abstract.
